images.caption: Orlando's Shannon Johnson, left, knocks the ball away from Washington's Stacey Dales-Schuman.

article.linkText: Mystics stay atop Eastern Division by beating Miracle
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Coco Miller had a game-high 17 points and
Vicky Bullett added 12 points and nine rebounds Monday night,
leading the Washington Mystics to a 63-51 victory over the Orlando
Miracle.

<photo1>

	   The Miracle fell three games behind the Eastern
Conference-leading Mysitcs.

	   ''You can't shoot the way we did and expect to have a chance to
win,'' Orlando coach Dee Brown said. ''We turned it over too much,
we didn't rebound, we didn't run our plays. We didn't seem to do
anything right.''

	   Nykesha Sales had 12 points to lead Orlando, which shot just 31
percent (19-for-61) compared to the Mystics, who shot 42 percent
(19-for-45).

	   Orlando was a dismal 3-for-20 from 3-point range for the game.

	   ''You aren't going to win many game shooting 31 percent,'' Brown
said. ''We have enough players on our team to win a game like this.
We didn't seem to have any uncontested shots.''

	   Washington scored 12 of the first 14 points of the second half,
increasing its lead to 33-22 with 14:25 to play.

	   ''We thought it was important for us to come in here and make a
statement,'' Bullett said. ''It's important to win on the road.
We've beaten a very talented Orlando team at our place and now
here.''

	   The Miracle didn't get within nine points of the Mystics the
rest of the way.

	   Bullett had 10 first-half points and three rebounds for the
Mystics, who made four of eight 3-pointers before intermission. Orlando
was 0-for-9 from beyond the arc in the first half.

	   Washington held the Miracle scoreless on 0-for-10 shooting for
the final 6:39 of the first half while building a 28-22 lead at the
break.

	   Jesse Hicks and Brooke Wyckoff combined for six of Orlando's
nine first-half turnovers. The Miracle turned the ball over three
times in the final six minutes of the first half.
